{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492689"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:41:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:41:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1131"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1131"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.05,0.43,0.02,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42142"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27144"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"361"},{"type":"tags","id":"2103"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"6628"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47353"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42142"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with increasing pain in his right calf and right foot over the past four weeks, worsened by exercise. Over the last two weeks he has had right foot pain which has been constantly present and is disturbing his sleep. He has a medical history of hypertension. His medications include perindopril. He is an ex-smoker with a 20 pack-year history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 155/90mmHg and BMI is 35kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Neuromuscular examination of the right leg shows that his right femoral pulse is diminished in volume and the distal pulses in the right leg are not palpable. A 0.5 cm shallow ulcer is present on the distal lateral aspect of the 5th phalanx but is non-gangrenous. His ankle:brachial index (ABI) is 0.3 and toe brachial index is 0.2. His right toe pressure is 20 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exercise treadmill ABI","Graduated exercise program","Doppler ultrasound studies","Pentoxifylline","CT angiogram"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man has chronic limb threatening ischaemia (CTLI). The change from intermittent claudication to resting pain with a development of an arterial ulcer is an index of the severity of the occlusive process and the patient now needs some form of active intervention. An ankle-brachial ratio of 0.3 is indicative of severe ischaemia. The primary goal is to preserve limb function via revascularisation and the use of an arterial imaging will help identify the diseased vessels and the optimal interventional strategy via surgery or an endovascular approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with CLTI are at increased risk of amputation and major cardiovascular events. A new classification system (WIfI) for CTLI defines the amputation risk based on wound, ischaemia and foot infection. He has a moderate risk of amputation (WIfI score of 1,3,0). He will need some sort of imaging to define the site, length, degree of occlusion and best interventional strategy for revascularisation. The most effective means will be a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E (assuming he has relatively normal renal function).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExercise treadmill ABI \u003C/strong\u003Eis performed for patients with intermittent claudication and a borderline ABI of 0.9. A post-exercise ankle SBP decrease \u0026gt;30\u2009mmHg or a post-exercise ABI decrease \u0026gt;20% are diagnostic for PAD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough a \u003Cstrong\u003Egraduated exercise program\u003C/strong\u003E is a first line management for claudication, (Fontaine Class I to Class III Peripheral Artery Disease), it will not be useful for this instance as the patients symptoms have progressed to CTLI. Revascularisation is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Edoppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E studies provide an anatomical location, extension of disease and its haemodynamics, the entirety of the vasculature can not be obtained and would be deemed challenging due to patient body habitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPentoxifylline\u003C/strong\u003E is an older medication for claudication and is no longer recommended by current major guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary goal in chronic limb threatening ischemia is revascularisation."],"references":["Conte MS, Bradbury AW, Kolh P, White JV, Dick F, Fitridge R, et al. Global vascular guidelines on the management of chronic limb-threatening ischemia. J Vasc Surg. 2019;69(6S):3S-125S.e40. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8365864/","Aboyans V, Ricco JB, Bartelink MEL, Bj\u00f6rck M, Brodmann M, Cohnert T, et al. 2017 ESC Guidelines on the Diagnosis and Treatment of Peripheral Arterial Diseases, in collaboration with the European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS). Eur Heart J. 2018;39(9):763-816. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/eurheartj/article/39/9/763/4095038?login=true","Mills JL Sr, Conte MS, Armstrong DG, Pomposelli FB, Schanzer A, Sidawy AN, et al. The Society for Vascular Surgery Lower Extremity Threatened Limb Classification System: risk stratification based on wound, ischemia, and foot infection (WIfI). J Vasc Surg. 2014 Jan;59(1):220-34.e1-2. Available at: https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0741-5214(13)01515-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27144"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1131"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27144"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-31T13:58:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T05:57:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42142"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m